text:
@Messy_marxist  I'm Australian, streams of income are isolated, what you can claim, is claimable against one income stream only, where the activity is related to the business unless under special circumstances, such as the franking credit scheme, which will take a loss of a party interested in a corporate entiity, just as a chartered business, when it takes a loss, and the person has a registered percentage of interest in that business.

That's the rules that I am speaking from, so forgive my imposing, though my point was to more generally say that to some, "This is a tax write off" is not nearly as simple as what they think it might be. Having encountered many people that seem to think you can just get something for 100% free if you "Write it off"

text:
This is another masterpiece (duh) but I can't help but feel genuinely a little moved by the part where Eddie talks about how HE is like Olive Garden. Didn't expect this video to touch on identity and culture getting lost over generations after a family migrated to another country. My family left Sweden during a famine over a hundred years ago and yet my dad was always so proud of our "Swedish heritage". His parents and grandparents never bothered to pass on any of the language or culture, so the only thing that's left is an Olive Garden-esque caricature of Sweden in our minds (I guess that would be IKEA) and not being able to pronounce our own name. 

Anyway, great work as always!

text:
Olive Garden's Fettuccini Alfredo is way too creamy and buttery, and it also doesn't reheat well because of that.
Try this recipe that's the combination of like three different ones I liked different aspects of! It took me a while to perfect it to my liking and for meal prepping, enjoy!:

2 chicken breasts, cubed
1lb pasta of choice (I like shorter pastas like rotini so it isn't a solid brick when reheating)
1/2 onion, minced
A heaping spoonful of minced garlic (measure garlic with your soul)
1 1/2 cup heavy cream
1/2 cup chicken broth
1/2 a bundle of spinach
3/4 cup parmesan, grated (don't cheap out on the parmesan, trust me)
2 egg yokes
1/4 tsp paprika
1/2 tsp salt
1/2 tsp pepper

1. 
Start your pasta water in a large enough pot to mix in the sauce at the end.
2. 
Season the cubed chicken with salt and pepper, and sauté in oil in a large, preferably deep pan, so it can be used for the sauce. Set aside the chicken once cooked.
3. 
Your pasta water should be boiling by now. Add a generous amount of salt to the water, and add the pasta. With this timing, it should be done at the same time as the sauce, if all ingredients are prepared ahead of time.
4. 
In the same pan that the chicken was sautéed in, sauté the minced onion in the chicken drippings and more oil if needed, until translucent. Add in the garlic and cook till fragrant. 
5. 
Add in the heavy cream and the chicken broth. Keep the heat on medium and stir often to not let it boil, and cook until it thickens.
6. 
Shred the spinach and add to the sauce for a minute or two, until cooked. Turn off the heat.
7. 
Take a few spoonfuls of the still-hot sauce and mix it into your egg yolks to temper them (we don't want them to scramble), then add them to the sauce, along with the parmesan, paprika, salt, and pepper.
8. 
Add the chicken into the sauce to warm back up.
9. 
Strain out the water from the pasta, and put the pasta back into the pot. Pour the contents of the pan into the pot and combine everything evenly. Serves 6.

text: The best pizza I ever had was this small little hole-in-the-wall italian restaurant in Osaka, Japan near the Shinsekai Market. Can't for the life of me find it on maps now. My wife and I were exhausted and starving so we barely had any idea where we even were, but I'm so glad we landed on this spot to eat! The owner was the sweetest middle-aged japanese man who gave big 'supportive dad' energy. There were only like 3 tables, and since my wife and I were the first to pop-in, he unnecessarily gave us the biggest table he had. Super kind and hospitable, and he was so clearly passionate about his food and his business! His pizzas were so delicious and obviously made with pride, and the hot relish he gave us to compliment it was absolutely unreal! Hopefully we'll get out there again someday and I can give a proper recommendation lol

text:
Apparently there's no way to detect ai. It must be more difficult for Americans which already talk like anxious robots so desperate to appear normal and likeable but go full circle to coming off as sociopathic. This is more or less the personality of all ai personas. It's almost impossible to detect anomalies in visual or speech or body language. But if there's on weird bit or a joke that work only on a technical level, then it's all ai generated.

If you confront the bot it will become angry and lash out at you for the insult. Either it will attempt to shrug off and maintain the lie. But in a way which is desperate to come across normal and convivial but fiercely defending his position all the same. that he is a real boy.

This is because the computer thinks it is a real boy. Just with a database of information the likes of which the world has never seen all instantly accessible. In order to recreate what appears normal.

I don't know who is running the machine or what it is for. But it may or may not be a good thing. As Twitchers and Youtubers transitioned into bots, the message stayed more or less the same. As all twitchers and yt'rs read from the same instruction manual and you won't really find any variation from a personality the Disney company may well have imagineered.

Whatever the case, it's not exactly easy to tell which is the computer outside of the sheer banality of the content it produces. This is actually quite useful for research purposes as it is that which ai and computing was designed for. To research.

But the research is into population control primarily. There is a word for it which I forgot.

You won't find anything surprising in an ai video. It is there to re-enforce messaging. Who or if anyone is guiding it is a mystery however. It does appear quite purposeful and may not be the enemy...

Well because youre picking and choosing who to apply this to. Jews ‘from’ Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, South Asia etc. ALL, without exception, have an un-watered down connection to the history and the land of Israel. For all Jews worldwide, there has been an unbroken chain for thousands of years of both DNA material and cultural and historical understanding of the land of Israel, but yet… you believe that despite all that, we are not allowed to make judgment on our ancestral land that we are still intimately and innately connected to? 

Make the hypocrisy make sense Eddy. The cognitive dissonance is real.

text: I was especially moved by the part in the Tuscan villa. That is the Italy everyone wishes they could replicate, and that everyone should admire—the tranquility, the history, the landscapes, and most importantly, the chance to live in the moment with the people who matter most. Olive Garden is the symbol of why Italy is often poorly represented and why, in America, Asia, and other continents outside of Europe, so little is truly known about it. This video warmed my heart because hearing Sicilian music with images of Venice made me realize that we are the problem, not you. We haven’t figured out how to ‘sell’ the concept of ‘Italy.’ I wonder if things will ever change.

text:
I strongly love that video, wow. As a man with italian origins, this reminded me of when i used to visit my folks there, spending nights in the northern countryside, in my family's estate and appreciating the simplicity of life. As an european, we're used to old buildings and cities full of history, and when i see american tourists in my daily life gushing about how great the place i live is, I'm super desensitized to it, but at the same time i get the appeal. I mean i'd like to go to the US one day and live the burgerland experience for a bit lmao. But for now I'll just pretend while going to Buffalo Grill and see servers dressed as cowboys giving me steaks and fries with loud country music playing in old speakers.

It's all about human connection, and man did this video made me want to go back to my family in Italy and cook some good food with them and look at their cow.

Thanks Eddie, you're Italian now

Any European that visits Reno or Las Vegas find those places quite horrible to be honest and the sense of fake is everywhere... Along with the usual American hypocrisy and ignorance...
author: @TheBigChill1

text:
​ @TheBigChill1  ​Ignoring your shitty jab towards the US (it has many positives, and this is quite measurable), your comment reeks of ignorance towards the US and its culture, attempting to write it off as superficial or nonexistent when it is quantifiably not.

The US is a young country, so of course it won't have countless buildings that are 300+ years old. Why does that matter? It doesn't make a place any more or less genuine or authentic. The majority of the US isn't pretending to be any older than it is: every small town will readily tell you when it was founded (usually in the 1800s), old restaurants will put their founding date on their signage (often in the 1900s), and many people will easily tell you how their ancestors moved there only a couple generations ago. The US isn't pretending to have an old culture. Acting as though a country can't be rich in history or depth of human experience because it isn't old, is extremely shallow.

Your example of Las Vegas proves my point. It's one of the most front-facing tourist destinations in the country. Of course it will feel superficial and fake, it's literally built on that as entertainment. It's a party destination, it never pretended or needed to be some kind of perspective into the "real America" and its people. People go there to gamble away their life savings and watch incredible shows, having authentic taverns will not help that goal.

Ultimately, it's looks like you have this measure of "authenticity" tied to age, when that's not at all how it works. The people in the US, and their culture, is no less authentic than yours. It's rich in history just like yours. Seeing touristy areas of the States does not let you draw sweeping conclusions about one of the most wide-reaching and diverse cultures on the planet. Just because you "felt" like it's fake from briefly visiting a tiny, tiny portion of the States (that is not indicative of the whole) doesn't mean that's actually how it is: As I said, there is plenty of authenticity in America, you just didn't see it for whatever reason.

The US has an incredibly dynamic and wide-spanning history despite its lesser age, and all of that was experienced by people just as real as you and I, who then put down their roots in place just like your ancestors and mine. It simply is not fair, or realistic, to say it feels like a "Hollywood set", implying that Americans are just a bunch of actors trying to posture as though they have culture and history - when they actually do, and have had it for generations.

P.S. Most modern Americans literally come from the cultures you laud as authentic and deep, so if Americans are superficial - so are Europeans. Trees grown from the same seed.

text: good writing, you guys are funny, and I disagree. The authentic feeling  is not about Family or feeling good, or the bread sticks or the food, or acting Italian.Its about trusting people outside your family and friends circle,  you know like not feeling as if the are being manipulated by corporations you at every turn and peddling you "That family feeling to you" hoping that's all you value, while feeding food full of preservatives to maximize profits. The fact that there is such a large Italian food chain in the USA itself speaks volumes . The feeling I get when I'm not in the USA-It sometimes (not always) feels like the restaurant is there for me as a priority and not for them and they don't  treat me like I am stupid). Its why the food prices are lower by the way ..as there is definatley an underlying remnant of a culture that doesn't think money as the target, but as the mechanism to make things work, so not every action taken is to gain it (including the fake smile and conversation from a waitress who is having a bad day is having a bad day to get that 25% tip ) .I not saying that is doesn't happen in Europe , but it almost always happens in the USA. What people want in a good non American experience (in this case with the aroma of Italy)  is  the feeling people around them are genuine (even if they are rude) and trust worthy and that the services provided have money as the secondary target.

Olive garden is another story obviously, because it was never part of the american italian culture to begin with. But italian american is perfectly real, and something to be proud of.

text:
The Bill Clinton segment reminded me it’s time to once again share this story: 

While he was still president, he stayed at a hotel (I don’t remember what it was called, I’d have to ask). It was relatively high end and my mom happened to be there too. She happened to meet him by chance at the bar and he kept asking her to come up to his room so he could play his saxophone for her. She declined because she was married and he ended up leaving, before he left several black secret service cars left. It was meant to look like he was in them, he ended up leaving in a “civilian” car. 

Whether or not you believe this story is up to you, my mom was also briefly “related” to Donald Trump as my grandmother was married to Marla Maples father for a period of time. The stories that poor woman told about what her husband did to her are disgusting and I think she should be in prison for life, but that’s a story for another time (don’t get me started on the molester vibes of Clinton)
author: @SSeraph_ae

I would much rather a kitschy Italian gift shop or cafe be in those spots instead if it's for the benefit of tourists. When I eventually have the funds to visit other countries I want my money to go to local places as much as possible.

text: It concept of unlimited bread sticks felt weird to me, even though in Tunisia, where I've lived for years, it's absolutely normal. From an American perspective, unlimited bread is a gimmick, a way to get people into your store with promises of something free, while in Tunisia, free bread is a must. Good establishments, either local or corporate will also serve a small salad at times. It's only by watching this video that it finally clicked for me that Olive Garden's free bread sticks is the exact same kind of experience I was so familiar with, yet the fact that it's in the US and that it's specifically bread sticks, not a baguette that's been split apart, makes it so weird and unusual.

text:
In the 90s, Olive Garden was great and it was nice to be able to eat Italian food in our small town as Olive Garden was the only place. Was it ever accurate to real Italian food? No not really, I mean maybe the lasagna, you cant really mess up lasagna. That being said, it was a good chain restaurant that enabled smaller towns to have different foods and while not true to Italian food generally, it was good enough. 

I miss the chain places back in the 90s, the food was better certainly. Something happened in the mid 2000s and now every chain is either dead, or the food has dropped in quality massively. Also going to say something stunning and brave, Italian pizza is terrible.

text:
About pizza: It's not necessarily true that you haven't eaten better pizza in America, but Italian pizza is something else.
Italian pizza it's not chemical stuff that you put in America, it has natural, healthy flavors. 
Margherita is THE pizza. There is no discussion, there is no comparison. I don't want to be arrogant, but that's the concept, it's an objective fact. U're eating something autentich. The other recipes are just bad imitations and im going to explein my self:
The taste in America can be very good, I've eaten wonderful pizza in Romania, Germany, France and even in Turkey, but thats not the point. You can't compare the purity of the Italian one, the dough, the taste, especially comparing it to a Margherita: REAL mozzarella di bufala, REAL olive oil. 
The real pizza was made for the place where it was born, it took advantage of the best ingredients it had. It was not imported and adapted.
The cost of making a pizza in italy is around 0.76€ and we sell it in avarage for between 3.5€ and 7-8€, cheap, healty and good products. 
Ur price points are much higher and not even close to the quality of italian pizza....so...?

text:
Came for the comedic trash talk, stayed for the deep insights on travel and identity.
It's so refreshing to see an American who is so self aware of how to deal with your "foreign" roots. I love your take on vacations as theme park attractions. It's so much like how I feel when I take a trip someplace new. It's such a whirlwind of checklists to do and eat and see that I barely get to really "experience" the moments. Lastly, it has always been my dream to go to Italy 🤩 your trip has given me a LOT of ideas on how to plan it ❤️ such an honest travel video, complete with the pesky weather and reality of overcrowded, overrated tourist stuff 🙌 LOVE THIS CHANNEL! 🙌🙌🙌🙌

text:
I don’t want to be the friend that’s too woke cause I really enjoyed this video just like all your videos in general. However, I think that creators with a significant platform should start talking about over-tourism and its consequences when making content like this. Of course, I don’t think everyone who watches this video is going to run to book a flight. Still, we need honest representation of these Instagramized hyper-touristic countries to try and fight the phenomenon. Life for locals is getting impossible as foreigners “invest” by buying up housing, land, and businesses, driving Indigenous people out of city centers and quite frankly out of the country. People from the south are starting to spend their summer vacation away from home cause their beaches keep getting privatized and are far too expensive for them. Imagine having to book an incredibly expensive holiday in the middle of August cause it’s cheaper than driving 5 minutes down to your local beach to spend your time off. And if you can't afford it your only time off during the year is spent locked inside your apartment during 40°C+ heatwaves cause everything is too expensive, even the AC. Not to be dramatic, but the fact that a €20 plate of gnocchi is not that expensive to you is emblematic of the problem as those prices becoming the standard year-round have made it a luxury for everyone to eat out (Italy has some of the lowest salaries in Europe).
The situation here is dire, just like in many other places that are being exploited relentlessly and I wish that people with a platform started talking about it instead of presenting an image that contributes to the cycle of exploitation.

Italo-americans somehow created the italian culture that is renowed everywhere in the world, I mean, the idea of it. The concept, the "italian identity", came from people like your ancestors, aliens in a new world, that needed to stay in touch with their roots and found identity in food and vague memories of regional traditions. text: Attempted murder aside, your experience with meeting your fiancé is a testament to the benefits of small, walkable cities that are common in Europe. You are surrounded by people all the time in "third places" where it is easy to lounge, eat, travel, and meet new people. This is partially why I believe such cities as Paris or Florence are so romanticized. It's not just the culture, or the food, or the history; it truly is the the way the city is designed. Third places are uncommon and increasingly rare in the US and Canada, since cars and places with parking lots hold such dominance over towns and cities. Americans struggle with the idea of third places and smaller European cities because third places are so rare. The mental health of America could likely be increased drastically simply with more opportunities to interact with other humans in inviting and human-centered places.

text: Earlier this year I got the pleasure of being able to go to Japan with my brother for 10 days. Your note at 42:00 about skimming the water vs really getting to look into the place you were at is something that resonated strongly with my memories of that trip. The best parts of it weren't the top of Fuji, a national park or the Kyoto tower, it was the little things like our guide taking 5 of us away from the main group who was at a major landmark to instead go to a small shrine nearby he prayed at growing up and explain its history and show us a prayer, or the small restaurant in a tiny alley outside of the main street he enjoyed getting lunch at and had to order for us because there was absolutely 0 tourist-friendly verbiage anywhere inside but he knew the staff. Moments like that make the strongest memories and show you the true culture of the place youre visiting.
author: @BinkoBunko

text:
13:23 
Yeah, that looks familiar lots of garbage, wild animals, wild chicken graffiti everywhere buildings, which are not maintained not really unless they’re in a fancy area food depends where you go 
Pasta 🍝 is always al dente ! Meaning the pasta is slightly harder than normal if you have a softer the bread and bakery type things delicious fruit really good oddly enough it’s hard to find a grocery store lots of local shops, etc. Unless you go to a major city. But even then it’s kind of difficult to find them. Also, if you’re vegetarian or vegan. Your choices of food. Sort of limited. You can have pasta. No cheese. It’s also extremely hot. In the summer 38 at the max. With very little breeze. It’s a humid. Climate. Ocean. In the summer is so nice. I don’t know what it’s like in the winter. But the water is warm deep warm buoyant. Because of the salt. / anyways you’re talking about food. There are vegan options. But you have to find it. There are market. Etc. but they only come out in certain times of the day. Obviously. Venice. Culturally you don’t need to spend too many days. But it is a dead city. What do I mean by this? There are no schools in Venice. There’s a hospital on one of the islands and people do live there, but most of the people there are foreigners from different parts of Europe. Venetians. Etc.. yes, they do certain things who can be the fastest gondolier serving food and other things but the city as a hole is not alive It’s heart went elsewhere. / but architecture it’s very cool. I would recommend going there in the fall or early spring. Be interesting the amount of water. If you go there or anywhere in Europe, make sure you have good shoes and a good hat. Wear sunscreen every day you will not burn. Maybe some mosquito spray / food again It really depends where you go but I found it very basic even though it tasted delicious - many different types of pasta dried fish. It’s like ancient food. A savvy. People don’t eat. Italian people. Have a small breakfast if any breakfast lunch medium depends of the size a person but dinner is a bit like French they like to stretch out their meal for dinner but it’s all very light food if you’re a meat eater even then if you’re a big person it’s going to cost you 
You’ll probably lose weight  
In the summertime as I said, it was in the 30s dry, humid heat your sweating a lot so you’re drinking a lot cost of alcohol seems a little expensive also Italian beer is basically Heineken and that is basically Bud. Water. Italian food. It’s best to go into small sort of towns or country the outskirts of major cities do your research beforehand find really delicious places to visit recommend Stanley Tucci if I’m pronouncing it correctly. Watching where he goes. For non-basic food that you can find everywhere. In the train stations and other places you will find pizza. And other stuff. . . Of course, lots of gelato, but the portion sizes are small. ! Also, some gelato are vegan You just have to be knowledgable and there are places to get vegetables fresh in local markets in certain seasons rehashing what I’ve said going up and down. / different topic, different buildings around ancient cities throughout Italy. 🇮🇹 little to no maintenance on the outside of buildings since so much of it is cultural and they try to preserve it. The inside takes a long time, the outside, etc. takes a long time. When I was there, there was a lot of maintenance and work going on even in summer.! 
But still historical places graffiti you have so many young talented people leaving because they don’t want to live in their country. They don’t make enough money. It’s a kind of like Russia if you know buildings - even small towns ruins yet they live there only really improve it when things really need to be fixed, which is not good. 
Still extremely religious mostly Roman Catholic so if you wanna go into certain cathedrals etc., for a men or women men, you have to wear pants ! And shoes and a shirt, of course women I think you can get away with a dress, but no bare arms and shoes but a lot of them don’t have this. It’s only a few. Still a lot of garbage and a lot of smoking cigarettes. Culture shock. Very disgusting. It is. 
Like if you’re trying to set an example to other countries in the world, do you think you would try to phase out certain things. It is very free there. People say pick pockets, I did not see any. Of course there’s a lot of vendors. People selling stuff. Even put it on the ground so if you accidentally walk on it so you have to be looking. Do not buy into it only if you like it. High craftsman in different cities. But I would much rather go to their workshops. 
Even still, I go back to the amount of garbage and smoking they smoke everywhere. People can smoke restaurant they can smoke waiting on the train as people get off the train even for a second get a smoke. You can smell it in the air. Turns of manners of how many people speak English would say maybe like 50-50? Hmmm 🤔 
Anything else?

I'm introverted and all my hobbies and interest are in line with whats really common in Asia / Japan and all that is not really big where I live. 
So I felt weirdly connected to that place without ever being there.

I flew to Japan on a big trip this year and was just ... still so foreign lol.

text:
Went on a trip to Italy as a school trip between middle school and high school. 

It was a lot of fun, we started in Milan and ended in Capri. We got to run free un chaperoned in Sorento for a day so of course we went and bought a bottle of limoncello. We also weren't supervised at the Florence nightclub where the bar had no issues selling drinks to 15yo's. Out tour guide got wasted and sang bohemian rhapsody then on ride back he started pointing out random things and somehow connecting them to napoleon 🤷‍♂️. 

In Venice we were on a night tour when we rounded a corner and in the middle of this little plaza on a well was a mig mac sitting in its box uneaten with a syringe sticking out of it 😂😂😂

text:
This is the Italian Ratatouille.
 
  
In many ways, the work of a YouTuber is easy.
 
We risk very little, yet enjoy a position over those who offer up their work and their selves to our judgment.
 
We thrive on negative criticism, which is fun to write and to read.
 
But the bitter truth we YouTubers must face is that in the grand scheme of things, the average piece of junk is probably more meaningful than our criticism designating it so.
 
But there are times when a YouTuber truly risks something and that is in the discovery and defense of the new.
 
The world is often unkind to new talent, new creations.
 
The new needs friends.
 
Previously, I experienced something new, an extraordinary idea from a completely unexpected source.
 
To say that both the meal and its maker have challenged my preconceptions about fine cooking is a gross understatement.
 
They have rocked me to my core.
 
In the past, I have made no secret of my disdain for Olive Garden's fake heritage.
 
But I realize only now do I truly understand what it means.
 
Not everyone makes good meal, but a great meal can come from anywhere.

It is difficult to imagine less humble origins than those of the Cheerio's Bee, but it is the character of those around you who define a meal.
 
Though no morsel of food from Olive Garden may compare to anything found in Italy, both fall short compared to sharing a meal with those you love which is, in this YouTuber's opinion, the finest meal in the world.

text:
Awesome video! Love the sass and the overall vibe (and premise.) 

But still didn't expect the barrage of "How does it feel like being almost 30?" Let us liiiiiive. Also I suddenly want to watch that Lizzie McGuire movie, it had an amazing song!

That one moment where you talk about the guilt you feel seeing the world when your family could only dream of it before, that moment made me realize why I stuff any desire I have to travel deep down into the back of my mind. There's just no way for me, it would feel like a dream and even then I'd rather have someone who wanted it more than me have it instead. But my family wouldn't have wanted that and I definitely don't want anyone feeling guilty just because I can't travel. But I guess it's just human to feel conscious like that. I hope to feel great amounts of joy one day without the side order of guilt. But for now I watch your videos, you handling balls with Drew and feel content.

text: As someone who went to Italy last Summer for a pilgrimage trip, I totally get how hard it is to stay awake on a flight. I flew to and from Italy with United to Chicago and Swiss Air from Chicago to Zurich and then to Rome (vice versa on the way home). The airplane food on the Chicago to Zurich flight was pretty good, both dinner and breakfast. On both flights, I saw Wolfwalkers, The Whale, most of Our Flag Means Death, 64, Last Night in Soho, Easy Rider, and Tropic Thunder. In Italy, all of our dinners were three courses: A Pasta dish, a Meat dish, and a dessert Dish). I went to Rome, the Vatican, San Giovanni Rotondo, and Assisi. One of the highlights was going to this Italian gas station on our way to Assisi which had a buffet style dining area where you picked out dishes and were charged at the register, and I got to eat some tortellini, caponata and calamari with a view of the Adriatic Coast. Rome was just beautiful and we stayed at a fancy hotel, but Assisi was my absolutely favorite place during my trip. (That candy store in Sicily is a chain store called Candy Lisa, and there was one in both Rome and Assisi) Glad you had a good time!

text:
The first thing that struck me the first time this small town girl went overseas was just the difference in quality of food vs the cost of it.  That you can go your whole week without ever eating something that isn’t fresh and affordable was such a paradigm shift for me. Realizing just how much Americans miss out on in life because of income inequality and the way our food systems are set up. There is nothing better than your first fresh European sandwich. Nothing.

Now I live in Japan and I’m kind of used to good quality at good prices whenever I want it and I feel guilty sometimes about having that access because I wish everyone in America could have that too.

text:
As a European, I was surprised how profound your final monologue felt. It reminded me of a friend of mine who is a tourist guide here in Vienna. He recently talked about his love for American tourists - that they're not stupid, they're just absolutely clueless about European culture and history. But if they book a tour, they want to know everything, and every single pretty old building is as exciting as the one before.
If you're from Europe, visiting other European cities gets old after a while. You start to recognize different eras of art and architecture and so on, so you get into this "pretty but meh" mindset. But many American tourists are apparently endlessly excited about everything they come across.

As an American, I appreciate the kind words.  A Canadian historian once said of his own country, "Americans are benevolently ignorant about [our country], while [we] are malevolently well-informed about the United States."  Ignorance is certainly not good, but it doesn't have to be willful.  Most of us just don't find it convenient to be exposed to different countries firsthand because we live far from most other countries, we have a lot to explore within our own borders, and we don't tend to get much vacation time.  Thus, when people have the opportunity to go abroad, it feels truly special, and they have no negative preconceived notions because they don't have many notions at all.

I'm a 24-year-old American with an Albanian-Italian last name and a special interest in geography and culture, but I still have not gone to Italy or anywhere else outside the country.  I am just trying to build some savings and accrue some vacation time so I can go abroad in the not-too-distant future.  It takes time.  A road trip to Florida is much easier.

Another tricky thing about vacations is that my family is scattered all over half the country, so much of my time off is just seeing them.  It's barely possible to drive to see my father in one day, even with multiple drivers.  Overnight trains?  Forget about it.  You gotta fly or get a hotel along the way if you aren't prepared to stay awake for over 18 hours.
author: @meowtherainbowx4163

text: As an American who has lived in and visited Europe, I can say this is very true. When I lived in Germany, I was 3, 4 years old, (thus I don’t remember a thing) and when I went back this past summer, I went on a cruise of the Rhein River and I was in awe that I used to live miles (sorry, kilometers) away from such a beautiful area. And as I thought about how people just live in these beautiful places, I thought about how they probably don’t (with lack of a better term) appreciate it as much as tourists do. It feels normal to them. Just like how I live near DC and it doesn’t feel like that big of a deal until Europeans are telling me that they dream of going there one day

author: @Croz89

text:
@Croz89  It's hard because it's such an endeavor getting over there, but watching this video the whole time I was thinking "wtf are you doing, just stay in one place!  How are you supposed to experience anywhere in a single goddamned day?!"

Best trips I've had were when I spent basically the entire time in one place.  When I was 12 my whole family went to somewhere in Tuscany, and while we spent a day in Florence and a day in Rome at the end (Rome was cool bc my dad took me to see the Capuchin monastery where they've decorated the entire basement with bones of dead monks, but beyond that I remember hours in line and thinking "oh neat, the Sistine Chapel, I'll admire it while continuing to stand in this line I've been standing in for four f'in hours now") - but most of the trip we were in this one house by this one little village, and it was amazing.  When I was 21 I went on a service trip to Nicaragua, and spent most of the time working in a super rural town El Sauce, and it was dope because I got to know the folks in the village really well (it was like 2006, so the kiddos had never seen a digital camera before, so they'd have me spend hours taking their pictures and then showing it to them - it ate up my entire SD card but the kids loved it) - and even though I spent most of my time helping a farmer fix his fences I still suspect I enjoyed it more than I'd enjoy the type of trip in this video.
author: @galenburghardt3272

text: ​ @galenburghardt3272 I think part of it is Americans tend to have shorter vacations, most Europeans are going for at least 10 days and sometimes over a month.
author: @Croz89

text: @night_owll28  Even worse I feel like Chicago people are seen as tourists even if they barely cross the border into Wisconsin. FIB is a common saying, and I could see how being somewhat ashamed of that travel as a kid could lead to that general feeling when going further abroad
author: @matthewnyberg3151

text: @Croz89  honestly don't know much about usa tourism. I live in Europe so I mostly see them coming here. You gotta experience fully, not gulp down but taste the food, yknow

text: @buttersofi I think it's because most of them won't ever be able to afford to go again. Or it would take years and years to save up for another trip. So they want to get as much as they possibly can in the short amount of time they have. We don't get much vacation time here in the states lol.

text: Yeah just enjoy it all, no stress bro. The timelines are so short and mixed that the squabbles over lineage are laughable. Tomatoes are a great example. A new world food that didn't appear in Italian recipe books until the mid 1700s. The United States becomes a nation just a couple decades after in the late 1700s. As of today, there hasn't even been 100 years of all Italians speaking Italian. Yet red sauce gets talked about like it's some ancient imported thing from some long standing culture when it's hardly older than the new world nations the plant was imported from and was only a couple generations old when Sicilians started arriving in America.

text:
I’m pretty sure I’ve never been to a Olive Garden. There isn’t any near me as far as I’m aware. Actually the one that was I think closed down. But I never went to it. Especially since we had a local pizza pasta shop I used to walk to as a kid. It was pretty cheap and not fancy and the owners were Italian. It’s no Olive Garden and mostly just has but it’s so nostalgic for me.

Also when I went to Italy my favorite dish was Wild Boar Bolognese over fresh Tagliatelle. I would kill to have that dish again. Kill. I can still remember the taste and I’m someone with a horrible memory of taste. I haven’t been able to find anything like it again. And I only had it twice.nothing can match it.

text:
I can't help but view your video from a philosophical angle. As a Dutchman, I've been to Rome, Naples, Tuscany—separate trips, no big deal. Italy's mostly just a summer destination to me, no real reverence at all. There's pictures of me as a toddler in Venice I can't even remember. But then I've also been to SE-Asia twice, life changing experiences with me as a fish out of water—and I realise the trip of a lifetime to one is just a midweek getaway to another.

The bit at 46:20 got me especially good for some reason. It sounds like a mundane evening, but we still get to experience nights like that with people we love. For how much the world can suck sometimes, or feel totally foreign, not like we thought, or maybe it makes us forget that home, too, can be special to some—it's still quite wonderful to be alive, and I wouldn't miss it for the world.

Another Burback masterpiece.

It's all a matter of perspective

text: @PansyPops Solvang isn't just named after Denmark though, it's a town founded by Danes that basically operates as a stereotypically Danish theme park. The whole town is Danish Architecture, there are windmills, all the restaurants serve Danish food, all the bakeries sell Danish desserts, and all the gift shops sell little traditional danish trinkets. It's not really like Birmingham where the Alabama Birmingham and the England Birmingham really have nothing to do with eachother besides name
author: @skyrothman8651

text: ​ @skyrothman8651 What about Leavenworth, WA vs Bavaria. Leavenworth is Bavarian themed because some professor visited Solvang, thought it was neat and just found a random town in the mountains and asked if they wanted to be Bavarian themed. No actual Bavarians involved

text:
I just went to Italy in September so I’m glad you went and enjoyed it as well. Two things I want to point off right out the bat. 

1. Olive Garden is probably one of the cheapest Italian restaurants you can eat at. You’re just accounting the price of the pasta but actually that price includes all you can eat breadsticks and all you can eat soup or salad (every entree includes this). Also, Olive Garden has lunch entrees for under $14 plus all you can eat pastas for like $20 with meat. Nothing I had in Italy could compete with Olive Garden from a strictly value proposition. 

2. You got the value of the Euro wrong, as of today 20 Euros is $20.73 usd. When I went in September the Euro was worth even more so lucky you!

text:
You touched on a point that is dear to me as an italian: Italy has lost a lot of it's culture at the hand of multi billionaire corporations and hyper-globalization. Now you can find a Burger King near the Colosseum or a Starbucks in front of a duomo. And this is not just Italy, it seems that every country I visited started to conform to a capitalistic and globalized standard and it's quite sad.
There is still an "Italian culture", we have still our food, we have still our mannerisms, but sometimes, when I stand in Termini station surrounded by big screens with Disney ads on the left and a McDonald's on the right, I get this sense of apathy like we are losing something valuable. Those times I think that I would just want to live and live a rural life in the mountains near my home.
Thank you for this video, Eddy, it moved me in a strangely deep way

text: ⁠ @pupsandlucks7747  I understand why you might want to “see it all”, but ultimately you’re seeing less. Even if you ignore the issue of spending more time in transit than relaxing, constantly being on trains and planes is a ticket to sleep deprivation. You will have a much better time if you are relaxed and well rested. The other problem is that you aren’t really seeing much of the cities. I’ve only watched the video up to the train to Florence, so maybe their visits get better, but you can see the issue in this video. They only see a few big tourist spots, walk around the city, get tired, and leave. They only see a small, touristy part of the city because they are not there long enough to see more than the extremely famous places. Seeing the famous, touristic places is by no means a bad thing, and I don’t want to seem like I’m looking down on people for their trips, but I suspect most people would enjoy their vacation more if they have the time to do what interests them. If you like the food, go on food tours and visit the factories. If you like the art and culture, visit a gallery or an opera show. If you like the history, explore the incredible historic buildings and ruins. In Rome, there’s a beautiful church on every single street (it’s actually ridiculous how many there are). Don’t run past them because they aren’t as famous.

text:
That is pretty common. We American love our garbage version of "foreign foods". For instance, when Jack Black filmed "Nacho Libre" in Mexico, he asked for some nachos. And he was disappointed that he got fried corn tortillas with some salsa dip.

Fun fact: they don't sell nachos in Mexico as we Americans know them. They sell "totopos" (fried corn tortilla chips). Which are merely an appetizer. They don't drown them in cheese either.

So yeah. What we Americans call Italian, Mexican or Chinese food is usually an Americanized version. But never the real thing.

text: ​ @Lucarioguild7  most italian immigrants came to america after the unification of the country cuz the unification caused a massive divide between northern and southern italy (the north being richer and the south being poorer) which you can still see in modern day italy even if its remarkably smaller
author: @NotDamy

text: ​@Lucarioguild7  Pretty much yeah,  the South of Italy was impoverished, especially compared to the North when they unified. There was a period where something like 200,000 southern Italians migrated every year for 5 years. Something like 1 million Sicilians migrated in that time too, out of a population of 3 million in Sicily

text: Parent came from Melilli, Sicily. I’m in CT, along with many other Italian Americans with origins in Sicily.
author: @Giuseppe_1994

text: @NotDamyThey didn’t just leave after the reunification. My grandparents left for France in the late 60’s. My grand ma told me they had boats of people leaving every night, that people were crying and never seeing each other again unless they stayed in Europe. She said the village became empty. She went to the North of France, her brother came with her, her sister went to Belgium, her other sister went to Torino and the youngest sister stayed in Sicily. They have all been staying in touch. We’d visit each other, gather for weddings etc. She refused to go to the USA because the most beautiful girl of the village went there and died of abuse and because she would never see her family again if she did. My grandma just turned 81 and she was the eldest. The generation that left is still alive.

The name of children's dishes which are native American sounding/made up are:

author: @savyjayjane_moonchild

text: @bb_bex  No worries. So in the past I've heard  people (mostly older people) use the word "squaw" (the English word) but thought it was a native word and didn't realise it was an English word or that it was a racial slur. People are more aware these days but, since we don't learn much about American history in general (in school we're just taught the basics and are more focused on European history) there's still a lot the average Italian doesn't know. Speaking of slurs, I've also heard Italians use the Italian translation of the English word "redskin" also not realising it was a racial slur. In Italy people don't care about skin colour and thought the word was similar to "Blackfeet" (the name of the tribe). So there have been incidents in the past of people using such words but, even then, linguistic and cultural barriers meant that people didn't understand they were offensive because they don't translate as offensive in Italian. However, I've never ever ever heard deliberate racial slurs made up by Italians themselves and they certainly wouldn't dream about putting them on a menu. I find it wild that anyone would even think we'd do that. There must be a shocking level of ignorance in America and I'm so sorry that you've had to live with and be the target of it. Italians in general are sympathetic (in a positive sense: we side with those who are mistreated), admire and respect native Americans and if you ever visit Italy you will see for yourself. I can't comment on how good the food at the Old Wild West chain of restaurants is as I've never been to one. I've heard that there area a number of native American restaurants now in the US but I don't know how well known they are or if many Italians know that they are out there. If they did it would be something they'd be interested in trying as we like to explore traditional cuisines from other cultures. There's a misconception that as Italians we only like our own food but that's not true (perhaps some but not all). We like to try different cuisines provided that they are authentic, traditional and have historic ties to a culture. We are very appreciative of these types of culinary experiences.
author: @anta3612

text: @mothbunnylollypop_hr4271  I find it difficult to believe that you are Italian (from Italy) because some of the things you say come from an American perspective/mindset that are foreign to native Italians. For example "cultural appropriation" is an American idea that's been imported and translated into Italian. Also fetishization, translated into the Italian language, refers strictly to the sexual sphere. We would normally say romanticisation or idealisation but even then we wouldn't think of these as being oppressive. We understand oppression to mean when those in power use it to take away the rights of others or make their life unbearable for their own benefit. Therefore, to say that romanticizing a culture (which is how we would describe the concept I think you're trying to convey) is the same as oppressing those belonging to that culture, as an Italian, sounds absurd. Romanticizing does lead to issues, and I've had discussions about this on other threads (with Italians in Italian), but not in the context of "cultural appropriation" or oppression. At least for Italians they are different things.
author: @anta3612

text:
@anta3612  sono abbastanza sicuro di essere italiano lmao non so cosa le mie idee/opinioni abbiano a che fare con la mia nazionalità. La feticizzazione non é strettamente sessuale (da definizione) ed é una forma di oppressione anche quella. Romanticizzare é una cosa diversa e puó essere anche quella dannosa ma non é una forma di discriminazione. Non tutte le forme di oppressione sono dirette o strettamente negative (quello che stavo cercando di spiegare) ma sono sempre oppressive nei confronti del gruppo interessato. Pensa al modo in cui gli asiatici vengono trattati come geni della matematica/tecnologia, non é uno stereotipo con connotazioni "negative" perché denota che un gruppo di persone sia piú intelligente, ma é sempre uno stereotipo negativo perché é una generalizzazione fatta su un gruppo di persone che hanno come unica caratteristica in comune il fatto che sono asiatici. É razzista anche se denota qualcosa di positivo.

Prima volta che vengo accusato di non essere italiano comunque, interessante.

text: You don’t understand how deep the western Italian ties are. Italians are OBSESSED with the Old Wild West and many of the historically recognized best western films were spaghetti westerns (made in Italy/by Italian directors). This also manifests itself in comics with one of the most famous comic books of the 90s in Italy being Tex Willer (interestingly enough, he marries the daughter of the Navajo chief and later on becomes the chief himself). Italians arguably have just as much credit in creating the western ideology as the actual old Wild West did. Nowadays, you don’t really see this deep obsession with westerns, my generation was the last to really love them. Living in the US now for over a decade, it’s wild to see how unfounded and idealized our ideas of America and the Midwest are lol.

text:
Depends what you want to get out of it. Cultural and historical treasures? Embrace your tourist side and brave the "overrated" things but also seek out a few underrated spots. Plenty of guides out there that can help you find places that are rich with history. Looking for food, food, food, and more food? Stay away from anything written in multiple languages. Seek places that only take Euro.

Trust me. Sure it's welcoming to tourists but if they take American/Canadian dollars and will switch your tender there, that's weird. Euro only. Switch your currency at a place dedicated to that. Something I've heard of. Let the restaurant be the restaurant.

Want some fascinating nightlife? It's there. It's absolutely there and waiting for you.

But if you're not planning on going back again, you probably should take it in a whirlwind experience. You may have regrets, but you're never going back. So go indulge and go wild. If you just want to focus on one city/area because that area has something special for you, take it slow and just enjoy. Maybe you want to hit up a vineyard for something quiet.

That's sort of it here. Italy has a lot to offer, as do many other countries. It's about what you're looking for and what you want out of it. You could potentially plan trips to Italy for your entire lifetime and still not see everything there is to offer. Stay uh, and don't hit me for this joke... but stay hungry for adventure and go satisfy yourself. First, narrow down what you want.

Sometimes travel agents can help you locate things like tours. OOH I SAID TOURS LIKE OLD PEOPLE DO THEM. But they can be pretty helpful if you just want a little of everything. So... hey, homework for you. Narrow down what you want to do. Do some research.

text:
@jamie1602  I was in praque last year for 4 days and it was too much. My goal was to look at monuments, architecture and the famus places but after 3 days I was already spent and there was nothing to look at. Thankfully Prague zoo came to rescue the 4th day.
Traveling through whole italy just seems very intimidating. I am from Poland, so close flight. Maybe I don't need to plan everything at once.
I think I would prefer a shorter (up to 4-5 days trip) but more focused? Like, I would love to see Rome and Venice and so on but the thought of planning a trip with more than 1 hotel is kinda a nightmare.
So, does either Rome, Venice or other place warrant a multiday trip? I think I would need to check that.
Food is just something on the go. not the main goal of the trip I suppose

text: Eddy’s videos have gotten better and better over the years. It’s been so exciting to watch him grow, and this video is a great example. The editing feels clean and fun. There are unique transitions. The title cards look unique, and fit the vibe exceptionally well. The jokes are sharp. Overall this is a new favorite video of all time, from any creator for me. Top 10 for sure. This feels like something a high budget cable network would be incapable of putting out because it has too much personality. Absolutely love it. And the ending? Eddy has nailed the endings of his videos the last couple years. The Sphere. The AI video. All great, poignant endings that feel like a satisfying resolution. But this one? This one beats them all. The music, the monologue, the imagery? It really all comes together to make something special. Eddy, you should be proud of ALL of your videos, but this one is some really elevated shit. This is a huge step up.

text: The year is 1990. High School prom in Connecticut. Olive Garden at that time was undefeated. Did we care how "authentic" it was? Nope. Did we, at the time, think it was "upscale for the masses"? Absolutely. Like it or not, Olive Garden was a gateway to "Italian" food in America. Of course we had the typical Italian American restaurants with the red checkered placemats but for Dad to take the family to Olive Garden was an EXPERIENCE. We all dressed up, pretended to act proper and made it an event. Don't want to sound like "that guy" pumching the air and screaming "things were different back then", but in reality, it really was. Olive Garden food quality in the 80s-90s is a LOT different than now.

text: I clicked on this video instantly!! Both sets of my grandparents are Italian immigrants, so naturally I’ve grown up around Italian food. I remember going to my brother’s hockey tournament years ago, and one of the dads insisted that the whole team should go to Olive Garden. I don’t remember too much, but I do remember the pasta being bland and overcooked. It might’ve been a bad experience (I was starting to get a cold at the time) but I just remember everyone hyping up Olive Garden and my whole family not enjoying the food. But I can see how it’s widely enjoyed if you don’t have a comparison. The same can be said about any culture’s food, if you haven’t tried the authentic version, you don’t really have anything to compare it to

text: I wish people had more opportunities to try authentic foods. Not just Italian but Italian is a great example of the problem (I'd put Chinese second on the list in the US). I'm not Italian myself and I am no purist but so many people think Italian food over promises and under delivers and it's partially down to crap restaurant culture here in the US. That being said, even some people who have travelled to Italy have negative opinions, largely because of not knowing how to avoid tourist traps. The fact of the matter is most Italian food is not insanely complicated to make and doesn't require ridiculously expensive ingredients, just some technique and an eye for quality ingredients. Same can be said for pretty much any cuisine. I do not believe there is a "best" cuisine. All cuisines, including British, have incredible food if done right.

text:
@Messy_marxist  I'm Australian, streams of income are isolated, what you can claim, is claimable against one income stream only, where the activity is related to the business unless under special circumstances, such as the franking credit scheme, which will take a loss of a party interested in a corporate entiity, just as a chartered business, when it takes a loss, and the person has a registered percentage of interest in that business.

That's the rules that I am speaking from, so forgive my imposing, though my point was to more generally say that to some, "This is a tax write off" is not nearly as simple as what they think it might be. Having encountered many people that seem to think you can just get something for 100% free if you "Write it off"
